  "texts": [
    "Robust Loss Function and SymmetryGhosh et al. [11] have theoretically proved that Cross Entropy (CE) and some other popular loss functions are not robust to label noise because they are asymmetric.",
    "On the other hand, symmetric loss functions like Mean Absolute Error (MAE) are robust to noise, but it takes a relatively longer time to converge.In order to combine the robustness of MAE and the fast convergence speed of CE, several partially robust loss functions are proposed.",
    "Notable examples include Generalized Cross Entropy (GCE) [12], a generalization of MAE and CE, and Symmetric Cross Entropy (SCE) [18], a combination of scaled MAE and CE.",
    "PHuber-CE [19] further introduces compositeloss gradient clipping, while OGC [20] improves this idea by learning an optimized clipping threshold, all of which can be viewed as hybrids that interpolate between CE and MAE.",
    "Furthermore, Feng et al. [21] leveraged the Taylor series to derive an alternative formulation that interpolates between CE and MAE, resulting in the Taylor Cross Entropy (TCE).Recently, Ma et al."
  ],
